'''Jambak''' (namo ilimiah: ''Syzygium malaccense'', {{baso-id|Jambu bol}}) adolah suatu spesies [[tumbuahan]] [[Tumbuahan babungo|babungo]] nan barasa dari [[Indonesia]] ([[Sumatra]] jo [[Jawa]]),<ref name="GRIN"/> [[Malaysia]],<ref name="GRIN"/> jo [[Vietnam]]. Tumbuahan ko kini lah marato taseba di babagai daerah [[tropis]], tamasuak di nagara-nagara [[Karibia]] sarupo [[Kosta Rika]], [[Jamaika]], [[Puerto Rico]], [[Suriname]], [[Republik Dominika]], [[Honduras]], [[Guyana]], jo [[Trinidad dan Tobago]].

Jambak disabuik jo bamacam-macam namo, di antaronyo ''Malay rose apple'' atau ''Malay apple'' ([[bahaso Inggirih]]), ''jambu merah'' ([[bahaso Malayu|bahaso Malaysia]]), ''jambu bol'' ([[bahaso Indonesia]]), sarato ''pommerac'' ([[bahaso Parancih]], diambiak dari ''pomme Malac'' nan aratinyo "apel Malayu"). <!--Despite the fact that it is sometimes called the otaheite cashew, syzygium malaccense is not related to [[cashew]]&nbsp;– an important distinction because cashews may trigger severe allergic reactions<ref>{{cite web|last=Rance|title=Cashew allergy: observations of 42 children without associated peanut allergy|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/14616109}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=cashew|url=http://www.allallergy.net/fapaidfind.cfm?cdeoc=259}}</ref> while syzygium malaccense does not appear to cause allergic reactions.<ref>{{cite web|title=rose-apple|url=http://www.allallergy.net/fapaidfind.cfm?cdeoc=4969}}</ref>

Highly ambiguous terms, such as "rose apple", "water apple", "mountain apple", ''pomarrosa'' or "plum rose" are sometimes used for this plant or its fruit; they can refer to almost any species of ''[[Syzygium]]'' grown for its fruit. The name "Otaheite apple" is used, too, (in Jamaica), but is better used for the [[Tahitian apple]] (''[[Spondias dulcis]]''); "Otaheite" is an obsolete [[Transcription (linguistics)|transcription]] of "Tahiti". Its [[Hawaiian language|Hawaiian]] name is ''{{okina}}ōhi{{okina}}a {{okina}}ai''; in [[Tonga]], it is known as ''fekika'', and in Fiji, ''kavika''; in [[Palau]], it is known as '''''rabotel''''' ([[Palauan language|Palauan]]).

The combination of tree, flowers and fruit has been praised as the most beautiful of the Myrtaceae family.<ref name=morton>{{cite book|last=Morton|first=Julia|title=Fruits of Warm Climates|year=1987|publisher=Florida Flair Books|isbn=978-0-9610184-1-2|pages=505|url=http://www.hort.purdue.edu/newcrop/morton/malay_apple.html}}</ref> The [[fruit]] is oblong-shaped and dark red in color, although some varieties have white or pink skins. The flesh is white and surrounds a large [[seed]]. [[Fruit preserves|Jam]] is prepared by stewing the flesh with [[brown sugar]] and [[ginger]].

