Malay apple is a strictly tropical tree and will be damaged by freezing temperatures.<ref name=pin>{{cite web|title=Malay Apple|url=http://www.tropicalfruitnursery.com/fruitproducts_m.htm|work=Plant Characteristics|publisher=Pine Island Nursery}}</ref> It thrives in humid climates with an annual rainfall of {{convert|152|cm|in|abbr=on}} or more. It can grow at a variety of [[altitude]]s, from [[sea level]] up to {{convert|2740|m|ft|abbr=on}}. The tree can grow to {{convert|12|-|18|m|ft|abbr=on}} in height. It flowers in early summer, bearing fruit three months afterward. In [[Costa Rica]], it flowers earlier, with ripe fruit in April. Coffee growers use the species to divert birds.

In Hawaii, ''Syzygium malaccense'' is called mountain apple. The [[Polynesians]], when they reached the Hawaiian Islands, had brought plants and animals that were important to them. The mountain apple was one of these "[[canoe plants]]" that arrived 1000 to 1700 years ago.<ref name=Whistler>{{cite book|last=Whistler|first=W. Arthur|title=Plants of the canoe people: an ethnobotanical voyage through Polynesia|year=2009|publisher=National Tropical Botanical Garden|isbn=978-0-915809-00-4|pages=241}}</ref>-->

